    <h2>Biography</h2>
    <img src="../photos/Mugshot.jpg" alt="Dr Matthew Simpson" width="150" height="150" class="fltrt">
    <h3>Academic Research Interests</h3>
    <p>My primary area of expertise is the use of computational techniques for solving differential equations and studying interacting random walk models. Using computation, together with a combination of other techniques from applied mathematics, I study a wide range of physical and biological processes. Previous research projects have focused on the study of flow and transport processes in porous media, salt water intrusion, the design and analysis of efficient methods for solving reaction diffusion equations and the implementation of high performance shock capturing schemes to study chemotactic travelling wave phenomena.</p>
    <p>More recent research interests include the study of collective cell migration, adhesive cell migration, moment dynamics models of cell population behaviour and latticeâ€”free random walk models. Studying problems from a wide range of fields has given me the opportunity to interact with a diverse set of collaborators including applied mathematicians, statisticians, experimental cell biologists and civil engineers. Working in such an interdisciplinary environment has given me the opportunity to use my computational skills to transfer knowledge across traditional boundaries that often separate different groups of researchers.</p>
    <h3>Academic Teaching Interests</h3>
    <p>My most recent teaching interests include first year calculus and analysis, and later year courses on differential equations and applied mathematical modelling.</p>
    <h3>Academic Service Interests</h3>
    <p>I currently serve on the editorial board of the Journal for Engineering Mathematics and the ANZIAM Journal. In 2015 I will co-direct the 51st annual ANZIAM conference.</p>
